{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"af60697d-01c4-4db7-9277-bab35a489430","content":"These are two distinct C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**Case 1: `&&` with `dynamic` and user-defined `operator true/false`**\n\nThe `&&` operator desugars to: `T.false(left) ? left : T.&(left, right)`. This requires resolving `operator false` **statically** on `left`'s type, then dynamically binding `operator &` because `right` is `dynamic`.\n\nC# 15 tightened the rules: the compiler no longer allows this mixed static/dynamic resolution when `operator true`/`false` are declared on an **interface** type (`IFilter`). Previous versions dynamically bound the entire expression; now the compiler rejects it.\n\n**Fixes:**\n- Avoid `&&` with `dynamic` — use the explicit two-step pattern or cast `right` first:\n  ```csharp\n  var combined = left & (IFilter)right;  // no short-circuit\n  // or\n  IFilter r = (IFilter)right;\n  var combined = left && r;              // both operands statically typed\n  ```\n\n---\n\n**Case 2: `ref readonly` return lambda — CS0518**\n\n```csharp\nvar fn = ref readonly int () => ref value;  // CS0518\n```\n\nCS0518 (\"Predefined type is not defined or imported\") means the compiler needs a BCL type that doesn't exist in your target framework. `ref readonly`-returning **lambdas** require the compiler to synthesize a delegate type annotated with metadata attributes (like `RequiresLocationAttribute`) that are only available when targeting **.NET 11 or later**.\n\nThis typically happens when:\n- Your `TargetFramework` is still set to an older TFM (e.g., `net9.0`, `net10.0`) while using the C# 15 compiler.\n- Or the required SDK isn't fully installed.\n\n**Fixes:**\n- Ensure `<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>` in your `.csproj`.\n- If you must target older frameworks, use a **local function** instead:\n  ```csharp\n  static ref readonly int Fn() => ref value;\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b729200e-03c0-4226-a4a1-8e98fef21be8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're encountering after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases.\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a change related to how `&&` and `||` operators work with `dynamic` operands. The `&&` operator is a short-circuit operator that relies on `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve the `true`/`false` operators at compile time for short-circuiting, but with dynamic binding, this becomes problematic.\n\n\nThe interface defines static operators `true` and `false` with implementations, which is valid in C# 11+. However, C# 15 may have changed how the compiler resolves these operators when dynamic types are involved in short-circuit evaluation.\n\nThe real issue is that `&&` relies on `operator true` to determine short-circuiting, but when the right operand is `dynamic`, the compiler can't fully resolve the operation at compile time since it needs to evaluate `operator true(left)` before deciding whether to evaluate the right side. This creates a conflict between compile-time operator resolution and runtime dynamic binding.\n\nIn C# 15, this became a breaking change—user-defined short-circuit operators are now disallowed when one operand is `dynamic` and the other type defines `true`/`false` operators on an interface, because the compiler can't guarantee correct dynamic dispatch of the compound operation.\n\nNow looking at another case involving `ref readonly` in a lambda... types on lambdas might require new infrastructure in the runtime that isn't available yet. The compiler is looking for a predefined type to support this feature, and when it can't find it, that's when CS0518 gets thrown.\n\nFor the dynamic operators issue, C# 15 probably tightened the rules around short-circuit evaluation with `&&` and `||`. When one operand is dynamic and the other has user-defined `operator true` or `operator false`, the compiler can't properly sequence the operations at compile time, which creates a conflict with how dynamic binding works. So it's now rejecting this combination outright.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda issue, CS0518 points to a missing predefined type—likely an attribute or runtime support that's required for `ref readonly` returns but isn't available in your target framework version. The `operator true`/`operator false` check happens statically, but when the right operand is `dynamic`, the `&` operator becomes a dynamic operation. C# 15 likely introduced stricter handling for this scenario—possibly disallowing short-circuit evaluation with `dynamic` operands when these operators are defined on an interface, since the interaction between interface static operator dispatch and dynamic binding creates complications.\n\nFor the first case, I can work around this by avoiding `&&` with `dynamic` altogether—either casting `right` to a concrete type, using explicit method calls, or switching to `&` if short-circuiting isn't critical. For the second case with CS0518 and `ref readonly` lambdas, the issue is a missing predefined type the compiler needs, so I'd either target the correct framework, use a local function instead, or define the missing type if stuck on an older framework.","outputTokens":2641,"requestId":"3019:2C244D:161AEAA:18EB3CB:6A067CC4"},"id":"3d312991-dd2e-40a6-8453-55de6fe6c1e8","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:55:08.567Z","parentId":"55b5829e-7deb-4556-a5b3-8b63e59c9ad0"}
